	<clause id="_definition_of_the_si" obligation="normative"><title>Definition of the SI</title><p id="_edd56f06-6617-4390-b9ff-dc66cde29e1b">As for any quantity, the value of a fundamental constant can be expressed as the product of a number and a unit.<note id="_023f07b7-23f8-427a-8ca3-538cde0b46f2"><p id="_f661e28d-c82f-417d-b024-3db8bcd068c3">Quotients of SI units may be expressed using either a solidus (/) or a negative exponent (<sup>−</sup>)</p>
	<p align="left" id="_76291e43-4a86-4b52-90cc-3a55f1ea7c14">For example,<br/>
	<stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mrow xref="U_m/s"><mi mathvariant="normal">m</mi><mo>/</mo><mi mathvariant="normal">s</mi></mrow>
	
	
(XML Line 000394): Hanging paragraph in clause
	<clause id="_definitions_of_the_si_units_unit_si_quantity_derived_base_units" obligation="normative"><title>Definitions of the SI units <index to="unit_si"><primary>unit (SI)</primary></index> <index><primary>quantity, derived</primary></index> <index><primary>base unit(s)</primary></index></title><p id="_86b5373a-7953-4113-881e-cff63384acd2">Prior to the definitions adopted in 2018, the SI was defined through seven <em>base units</em> from which the <em>derived units</em> were constructed as products of powers of the <em>base units.</em> Defining the SI by fixing the numerical values of seven defining constants<index><primary>defining constants</primary></index> has the effect that this distinction is, in principle, not needed, since all units, <em>base</em> as well as <em>derived units</em>, may be constructed directly from the defining constants<index><primary>defining constants</primary></index>. Nevertheless, the concept of base and derived units is maintained because it is useful and historically well established, noting also that the ISO/IEC 80000 series<index><primary>ISO/IEC 80000 series</primary></index> of Standards specify base and derived quantities which necessarily correspond to the SI base and derived units defined here.</p>
	<clause id="_base_units" obligation="normative"><title>Base units</title><p id="_a560849e-d896-4141-b0f4-654ebf46466c">The base units of the SI are listed in <xref target="table2"/>.
	<index-xref also="false"><primary>unit, base</primary><target>base unit(s)</target></index-xref>
	<index to="base_units"><primary>base unit(s)</primary></index>
	<index to="def_base-units"><primary>definitions of base units</primary></index>
