	<annex id="_historical_notes_on_the_development_of_the_international_system_of_units_and_its_base_units" obligation="normative"><title>Historical notes on the development of the International System of Units and its base units</title><clause id="_part_1_the_historical_development_of_the_realization_of_si_units_realization_of_a_unit_système_international_dunités_siinternational_system_of_units" obligation="normative"><title>Part 1. The historical development of the realization of SI units <index to="realization_unit-3"><primary>realization of a unit</primary></index> <index-xref also="false"><primary>Système International d’Unités (SI)</primary><target>International System of Units</target></index-xref></title><p id="_db5788a2-782e-4bc9-aee2-3d591bf12a8a">Experimental methods used for the realization of units and which use equations of physics are known as primary methods. The essential characteristic of a primary method is that it allows a quantity to be measured in a particular unit directly from its definition by using only quantities and constants that themselves do not contain that unit.
	<index><primary>length</primary></index><index><primary>second (<stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mrow xref="U_NISTu3"><mi mathvariant="normal">s</mi></mrow>
	
	
	
